      "id": "recursive-dfs",
      "name": "Approach 1: Recursive DFS O(n)",
      "summary": "Use post-order DFS to compute height and balance status simultaneously in one pass.",
      "timeComplexity": "O(n)",
      "spaceComplexity": "O(h) where h is tree height",
      "ladders": [
        {
          "level": 0,
          "title": "Full Problem — Check if Binary Tree is Balanced",
          "desc": "Complete recursive DFS solution that returns both balance status and height for each subtree.",
          "explanation": "A height-balanced binary tree requires that for every node the absolute difference in heights of left and right subtrees is at most 1, and both subtrees are balanced. The recursive DFS approach performs a post-order traversal, computing height and balance in one pass. For each node, recursively get (balanced, height) from left and right subtrees. If either subtree is unbalanced or height difference >1, return (false, -1). Otherwise return (true, 1 + max(leftHeight, rightHeight)). Base case: null node returns (true, 0). Time: O(n). Space: O(h). Real code pattern: def isBalanced(root): def dfs(node): if not node: return True, 0; leftB, leftH = dfs(node.left); rightB, rightH = dfs(node.right); if not leftB or not rightB or abs(leftH - rightH) > 1: return False, -1; return True, 1 + max(leftH, rightH); return dfs(root)[0]",
          "examples": [
            {
              "input": "root = None",
              "output": "true",
              "trace": "Root is None → immediately return true (balanced) with height 0."
            },
            {
              "input": "root = 1 (left = 2, right = 3)",
              "output": "true",
              "trace": "Left subtree (2): null children → balanced, height 1. Right subtree (3): null children → balanced, height 1. At root: difference = 0 ≤1, both subtrees balanced → overall true."
            }
          ],
